[EEE virus transmission has ended for the season in those states that have had killing frosts that bring mosquito activity to a halt. It is unlikely that additional human or equine EEE cases will occur in 2019, with the possible exception of Florida. As mentioned above, in a series of ProMED-mail posts and by the CDC, 2019 has indeed been an active year for EEEV transmission with cases in humans and in horses. The CDC EEE web page (https://www.cdc.gov/easternequineencephalitis/index.html) states, "As of 19 Nov 2019, CDC has received reports of 36 confirmed cases of eastern equine encephalitis virus disease for this year [2019], including 14 deaths. Cases have been reported from the following 8 states: Connecticut (4), Indiana (1), Massachusetts (12), Michigan (10), North Carolina (1), New Jersey (4), Rhode Island (3), and Tennessee (1)."

The report above does not mention cases of EEE in horses. There have been triple the number of horse cases over human cases this year (2019). Horse owners in eastern and upper midwestern states should vaccinate their animals. As the authors above state, there is no commercially available vaccine for humans. The sporadic nature of the relatively few human cases that occur annually and the extremely high cost of developing a vaccine for people and the difficulty in identifying a target population to vaccinate, as the authors mention, are currently insurmountable barriers to EEEV vaccine development. - Mod.TY

The citation for the reference mentioned above is: Morens DM, Folkers GK, Fauci AS. Eastern equine encephalitis virus -- another emergent arbovirus in the United States. N Engl J Med. 2019; 381(21): 1989-92; https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMp1914328.

